In article <1993Aug15.172607.22902@indirect.com>, Bill Moore (bimo@indirect.com) writes:
>Then if I look at my card, knowing my PIN, I can determine how to get
>anybody's pin, provided I can read their card.  Are those stripes encoded
>in any way?  It seems if security were this lax and the stripes readable
>with any mag stripe reader, these cards would be getting ripped off all
>the time.
>
>-- 
>bimo@indirect.com  (Bill Moore - Phoenix, Arizona)
>

They do; but banks are somehow reluctant to admit to it. (can't imagine
_why_!)

You don't actually /need/ a mag-stripe reader; there are companies that
peddle a fluid that will display where the 1's and 0's are on magnetic
tape, and what their polarities are.  Originally intended for legitimate
recovery of data, it could be subverted by a suitably inventive mind....
 

